enton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England","Liversedge, Yorkshire, England":"Liversedge, Yorkshire, England"},"cs":{"1370–":"1370–Zesnulý","1370–Male":"1370–Zesnulý","1375–Female":"1375–Zesnulá","1398–1450":"1398–1450","1340–Male":"1340–Zesnulý","1345–Female":"1345–Zesnulá","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Fenton, Nottinghamshire, Anglie","Liversedge, Yorkshire, England":"Liversedge, Yorkshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1370–":"1370–Afdød","1370–Male":"1370–Afdød","1375–Female":"1375–Afdød","1398–1450":"1398–1450","1340–Male":"1340–Afdød","1345–Female":"1345–Afdød","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England","Liversedge, Yorkshire, England":"Liversedge, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"1370–":"1370–Overleden","1370–Male":"1370–Overleden","1375–Female":"1375–Overleden","1398–1450":"1398–1450","1340–Male":"1340–Overleden","1345–Female":"1345–Overleden","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England","Liversedge, Yorkshire, England":"Liversedge, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1370–":"1370–Deceased","1370–Male":"1370–Deceased","1375–Female":"1375–Deceased","1398–1450":"1398–1450","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1345–Female":"1345–Deceased","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England","Liversedge, Yorkshire, England":"Liversedge, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fenton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places, in Yorkshire, Lincolnshire, Northumberland, Staffordshire, and Nottinghamshire, so called from Old English <i>fenn</i> ‘marsh, fen’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’.","Irish: English surname adopted by bearers of Gaelic <i>Ó Fionnachta</i> or <b>Ó Fiachna</b> ‘descendant of <i>Fiachna</i>’, an old personal name Anglicized as <b>Feighney</b> and sometimes mistranslated as   Hunt   (see   Fee   1 and   Finnerty  ).","Scottish: habitational name from Fenton in East Lothian."],"variants":[{"name":"Hunt","meanings":["English (southwestern): occupational name for a hunter, from Middle English <i>hunte</i> ‘hunter, huntsman’ (Old English <i>hunta</i>). The term was used not only of the hunting on horseback of game such as stags and wild boars, which in the Middle Ages was a pursuit restricted to the ranks of the nobility, but also to much humbler forms of pursuit such as bird catching and poaching for food. The word seems also to have been used as an Old English personal name and to have survived into the Middle Ages as an occasional personal name. Compare   Huntington   and   Huntley  .","Irish: adopted for various Irish surnames containing or thought to contain the Gaelic element <i>fiadhach</i> ‘hunt’; for example <b>Ó Fiaich</b> (see   Fee  ) and <b>Ó Fiachna</b> (see   Fenton  ).","Possibly an Americanized form of German   Hundt  ."]},{"name":"Fantom","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>fantom</i>, <i>fainton</i> ‘apparition, ghost’. There has been some confusion with   Fenton  ."]},{"name":"Finton","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Fenton  ."]},{"name":"Fenty","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Fenton  ."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese: written 井伊 ‘well’ and ‘that’, the name one of Japan's great daimyō families, originally based in Tōtōmi (now part of Shizuoka prefecture), later in Kōzuke (now Gunma prefecture) and Ōmi (now Shiga prefecture). Other variants of the name substitute either character with similar sounding characters such as 飯 ‘cooked rice’, 居 ‘residence’, and so forth. It was formerly Romanized as <b>Iyi</b>. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Roman number <i>II</i> (meaning ‘the second’, i.e. ‘the younger’ of the two bearers of the name) is apparently also counted as a surname <i>Ii</i>.","History: Ii Naomasa (1561–1602) was awarded lands in Kōzuke and Ōmi for his service in the civil wars that won the shōgunate (military dictatorship) for Tokugawa Ieyasu. His family built the beautiful castle of Hikone, which still stands. His descendant Ii Naosuke (1815–1860) ruled Japan for two years as Tairō (Great Elder) and played a major part in signing treaties that opened Japan to foreign trade at the end of the Tokugawa Shōgunate. He was assassinated by adherents of the anti-foreign party."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":85,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Fenton II was born in 1370, in Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England, his father, Henry I Fenton, was 30 and his mother, Isabel Mering, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Catherine Bretofte. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1370–":"1370–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1375–Female":"1375–Surnud","1398–1450":"1398–1450","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England","Liversedge, Yorkshire, England":"Liversedge, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1370–":"1370–Kuollut","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1375–Female":"1375–Kuollut","1398–1450":"1398–1450","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1345–Female":"1345–Kuollut","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England","Liversedge, Yorkshire, England":"Liversedge, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1370–":"1370–Décédé","1370–Male":"1370–Décédé","1375–Female":"1375–Décédée","1398–1450":"1398–1450","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","1345–Female":"1345–Décédée","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Fenton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Fenton, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre","Liversedge, Yorkshire, England":"Liversedge, Everwyck, Angl